external_knowledge:
- "Top 3 campaigns" refers to the campaigns with the highest total impressions;
- "Shine the brightest" is a metaphor for having the highest number of impressions;
- "Lit up the digital world" is a metaphor for the number of impressions, which is the number of times an ad is displayed.

- "Search campaigns" are advertising campaigns that target users based on search queries;
- "Impressions" are the number of times an ad is displayed;
- "Clicks" are the number of times an ad is clicked;
- "Conversions" are the number of times an ad leads to a desired action, such as a purchase or sign-up;
- "CTR" (Click-Through Rate) is calculated as (clicks / impressions) * 100;
- "CPM" (Cost Per Mille) is the cost per 1,000 impressions;
- "CPC" (Cost Per Click) is the cost per click;
- "CPA" (Cost Per Acquisition) is the cost per conversion.

- Ad groups are collections of ads that share targeting settings and bids.;
- Impressions are the number of times an ad is shown.;
- Clicks are the number of times an ad is clicked.;
- CPM (Cost Per Mille) is the cost of 1,000 impressions.;
- The average CPM is calculated by dividing the total cost by the total number of impressions, then multiplying by 1,000 to get the cost per 1,000 impressions.

sql:
SELECT campaign_id, COUNT(ad_group_id) AS ad_group_count
FROM ad_groups
GROUP BY campaign_id;

external_knowledge:
- "Blossomed the most" refers to campaigns with high performance metrics;
- "Seen by more than a thousand eyes" refers to campaigns with more than 1000 impressions;
- "Clicked on by more than fifty curious fingers" refers to campaigns with more than 50 clicks;
- "Click-through rate that surpasses the whisper of 1%" refers to a click-through rate greater than 0.01;
- "Bountiful harvests" refers to the total number of conversions.

- Campaign performance is evaluated based on multiple metrics, including impressions, clicks, and conversions;
- The budget is considered as a crucial factor in campaign performance, though the query ranks campaigns primarily by conversions;
- The campaign hierarchy is used to ensure that the performance metrics are aggregated correctly across different levels of the campaign structure.

- "campaign" refers to a marketing campaign;
- "impressions" represent the number of times an ad is displayed;
- "most impact" implies the highest number of impressions.

- "Blooms" refer to campaigns;
- "Petals" refer to ad groups;
- "Sun" and "light" refer to impressions.

- "Bask in the glow of the most attention" refers to the ads with the highest number of impressions;
- "Top 3 ads in each ad group" means the ads are ranked within their respective ad groups, and only the top 3 are selected based on the total impressions;
- "From the most to the least attention-grabbing" indicates the results are ordered by total impressions in descending order.

- "Performance" in this context includes the sum of impressions, clicks, and conversions;
- "Average performance" is calculated by dividing the total performance by the number of distinct ads;
- "Client spend levels" are determined by the total budget spent by each client across all their campaigns.

- "Recent ads" refers to ads that started within the last 30 days;
- "Budget over 1000" means the ad group budget is greater than 1000;
- "Version greater than 1" means the campaign has been updated at least once.

- ROI is calculated as the total number of conversions divided by the total budget spent;
- The query aims to identify the most effective client in terms of marketing efficiency;
- A higher ROI indicates better performance in converting ad spend into conversions.
